Appian Interview Experience
Pre-requisites - Java
Number of rounds - 4
Online Assessment - Coding round
Technical Round 1 - 45 minutes
Technical Round 2 - 45 minutes
HR Interview - 20 minutes
Online Assessment
There were 5 MCQ Questions and 2 coding questions.
The MCQ questions were debugging, predict the output type questions.
The coding questions (Java was the only language available) were
1.A easy problem involving HashMap. (Leetcode easy level)
2.Breadcrumbs in a website.
Given an ArrayList<ArrayList<String>>navigations generate the actual navigation tree.
Example
[
[“Root”, “Profile”, “Settings”],
[“Root”, “Profile”, “Albums”],
[“Root”, “Settings”],
]
Helper class TreeNode was given
class TreeNode {
string value;
ArrayList<TreeNode>children;
void addChild(TreeNode c){
this.children.add(c);
}
//a function to print the tree
}
The function that you need to implement is
void createTree (ArrayList<ArrayList<String>> paths) {
}
The solution is
import java.util.*;
class TreeNode{
string value;
ArrayList<TreeNode>children;
TreeNode(string str) {
this.value = str;
}
void addChild (TreeNode c) {
this.children.add(c);
}
}
class answer{
void createTree(ArrayList<ArrayList<String>> paths){
TreeNode parent = new TreeNode("Root");
HashMap<String, TreeNode> map = new HashMap<>();
for (ArrayList<String>path : paths) {
for (int i = 1 ; i < path.size(); i++) {
boolean alreadyIncluded = false;
String parent = path.get(i-1);
String current = path.get(i);
for (TreeNode child : parent.children){
if (child.value == current){
alreadyIncluded = true;
break;
}
}
if (!alreadyIncluded) {
TreeNode child = null;
if (!map.containsKey(current)){
child = new TreeNode(current);
map.put(current, child);
}
else{
child = map.get(current);
}
parent.addChild(child);
}
}
}
}
}
38 students were shortlisted for the interview.
First Technical Round
1.A coding question (Find the majority element in the array)
https://leetcode.com/problems/majority-element/.
You have to solve the problem in constant space and in linear time. Use the Moore’s voting
algorithm(https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/boyer-moore-majority-voting-algorithm). You have
to actually code out the solution in a editor and pass the test cases.Then a follow up
question on how to find the element that occurs more than 40% of the time in the array was
asked.The constraint given was constant space. Sorting the array taking the count would
work. Time given for the coding question was 20 minutes. Then resume related questions
were asked.As I had mentioned React JS in my skills questions related to React was asked.
1. Advantages of using React
2.What is prop drilling.
3.UseContext hook.
4.What is JSX.
5.Advantages of using JSX over traditional JS.
Difficulties faced during the project. I mentioned how deploying the project was difficult as
the server cache was less. So they asked about the deployment experience in azure and
how to remote sign in and check logs.
2nd Technical Round.
This round again started with a technical question. The technical question was the same
breadcrumbs question asked in the OA. A few modification and edge cases in the question
was asked. What to do if there were two paths to a particular page and so on. Again you had
to code the solution within 20 minutes. Then Resume related questions were asked, this
round focused on my intern experience. My intern work was discussed and questions related
to it was asked.
3rd HR Round.
The HR Round was like Ask Me Anything session with the HR. There weren’t much HR
questions asked just normal talk about college.I asked about their work culture, how the
company works and about their product.
Finally 4 from CSE were selected for FTE.
Key takeaways.
1.Be strong in aptitude(mostly overlooked) and in DSA.
2.Know everything that’s in your resume.
3.Sometimes you may not get shortlisted even if you did the Online Assessment well, it
depends on a variety of factors.
4.Try to have a CGPA above 9 or 8.5.
5.Deploy your projects.

NVIDIA – INTERVIEW EXPERIENCE 

About the Company: 
NVIDIA (short for Invention of Visual Display Interface Accelerator) is a global leader in 
graphics processing technology and artificial intelligence computing. Known for its 
powerful GPUs, NVIDIA revolutionized gaming, professional visualization, and high-
performance computing. Beyond graphics, it plays a key role in advancing AI, deep 
learning, data centres, and autonomous vehicles through its CUDA platform and NVIDIA 
AI frameworks. 

NVIDIA India, with offices in Bengaluru, Hyderabad, and Pune, serves as a major R&D 
and engineering hub, driving innovations in GPU architecture, AI research, and cloud 
technologies. The teams focus on developing next-generation computing solutions that 
power industries ranging from gaming to scientific research and enterprise AI. 

Role Offered:  System Software Engineer 

Selection Process:  
1. Online Assessment 
2. Technical Interview 
The Online Assessment was conducted at CUIC on 25/09/2025. But the 
shortlisted candidates were announced on 13/10/2025, So if you are 
confident enough in your performance be patient.   
Online Assessment: 
• Duration: 1 hour 
• Platform: HackerRank 
• Pattern: 2 coding questions (one easy and one hard) & 27 MCQs 
including C/C++ fundamentals, OS, DSA, Debug and Aptitude. 
• For the aptitude questions each carries 3 points, for technical 
questions each carries 2 points, the easy question carries 10 or 15 
points and the hard one carries 75 points. 
The MCQs were split into two sections 15 aptitude questions and 12 
technical questions. For the aptitude section focus on permutation, profit 
percent, Chain rule problem and basic math questions. 

For the technical questions focus on OS concepts like scheduling 
algorithms, paging, C/C++ fundamentals like string literals, pointers, static 
variables and functions, bit manipulation, signed/unsigned char or int, and 
some DSA analyzes and debug questions. 
For example, 
unsigned int y = 2; 
int x = -2;  
if(x > y) 

printf(“X is greater than Y”); 
else 

printf(“Y is greater than X”); 

Output: X is greater than Y 

This question was asked to me even in the technical interview. 
unsigned char ch = 0; 
int count = 0; 
while(++ch <= 255) 

count++; 
printf(“%d”, count); 
Output: This forms an infinite loop.  
For the DSA, the easy question should be solved only using C and the hard 
question can be solved using either C/C++ ( C and C++ are the only 
programming languages available for the OA ).  
The first question is powers of two where a binary char array is provided 
and you have to check whether is it a power of 2.  
( The logic is based on the mathematical property that a positive number is 
a power of two if and only if its binary representation contains exactly one 
'1' ) 
int isPowerOfTwo(const char *str) { 
    int one_count = 0; 
    int i = 0; 
    while (str[i] != '\0') { 
        if (str[i] == '1') { 
            one_count++; 
        } 
        i++; 
    }   
    return (one_count == 1); 
} 
int main() { 
    int n; 
    int i; 
    char binary_string[101]; 
    scanf("%d", &n); 
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) { 
        scanf("%100s", binary_string); 
        if (isPowerOfTwo(binary_string)) { 
            printf("True\n"); 
        } else { 
            printf("False\n"); 
        } 
    } 
    return 0; 
} 

The second question is a hard recursion based string question. 
Link: https://leetcode.com/problems/special-binary-
string/description/ 

These both questions were repeated for the past two years so it is 
important not only for NVIDIA but also for any companies to research about 
the pattern of the hiring and previously asked question’s patterns. 
You can find these patterns in platforms like leetcode, gfg, and 
sometimes reddit. ( https://leetcode.com/discuss/post/5896082/nvidia-
software-engineering-internship-6-ngsp/ ) 

Technical Interview: 
The experience may wary but I was asked one DSA question and everything 
else was about bit manipulation and C/C++ fundamentals. 
Note: It is very important to revise the questions that were asked during 
the OA for this round, some questions were asked from the OA and even 
the interviewer mentioned this (like the question that I mentioned above). 

 The DSA question is a linked list problem, 
Link:  https://leetcode.com/problems/reverse-nodes-in-k-
group/description/ 
And for the other technical questions I was asked 
bool Dummy(unsigned int n) 
{ 

if(n <= 0) 


return false; 

else 


return !(n & (n-1)); 
} 
So you have to provide an appropriate name for the given function. ( This is 
a function to find if the given number is a power of 2) 
Are these valid or throws an error? 
If( x == 10)  ans: (valid) 
If( 10 == x)  ans: (valid) 
If( x = 10)   ans: (valid) 
If( 10 = x) ans: (Invalid) 

And finally I was asked how a float point number is represented and stored 
in binary inside computer memory. ( Ans: using Sign bit, Exponent and 
Mantissa) 

